# 11. Call it from your existing snapshot flow

Your existing service probably determines whether the incoming snapshot creates, updates, or does nothing.

Conceptually:

```java
@Transactional
public UserSnapshotResponse processSnapshot(
        UserSnapshotRequest request
) {
    SnapshotResult result = saveSnapshot(request);

    UserEntity user = result.user();

    switch (result.operation()) {
        case CREATED ->
                userPingSynchronizationService.createInPing(user);

        case UPDATED ->
                userPingSynchronizationService.updateInPing(user);

        case DELETED ->
                userPingSynchronizationService.deleteFromPing(user);

        case NO_CHANGE -> {
            // Do not call Ping.
        }
    }

    return buildResponse(result);
}
```

If you have an operation enum:

```java
public enum SnapshotOperation {
    CREATED,
    UPDATED,
    DELETED,
    NO_CHANGE
}
```

For a status change to inactive, it may be safer to PATCH Ping:

```java
status = INACTIVE
```

instead of calling `DELETE`.

That flow becomes:

```java
case DELETED -> {
    user.setStatus(UserStatus.INACTIVE);
    userPingSynchronizationService.updateInPing(user);
}
```

Confirm this with Ping.

